definition.value: A pyridine nucleoside comprising 4-imino-1,4-dihydro-3-pyridinecarboxylic acid as the nucleobase having the beta-ribofuranosyl moiety attached at position 1. A toxin produced by poisonous mushrooms.
A monosaccharide sulfate that is D-galactose carrying a single sulfo substituent at position 6.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of glycolaldehyde phosphate; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A zwitterion that is derived from 2,5-diimino-3,4-bis(indol-3-yl)hexanedioic acid by deprotonation of both carboxylic acid groups and protonation of both amino groups; major species at pH 7.3.

A zwitterion that is derived from 3,4-bis(7-chloroindol-3-yl)-2,5-diiminohexanedioic acid by deprotonation of both carboxylic acid groups and protonation of both amino groups; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-oxo Delta(1)-steroid that is androst-1-ene substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 17.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-19,20-epoxydocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,19Z)-16,17-epoxydocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,16Z,19Z)-13,14-epoxydocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-10,11-epoxydocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-19,20-epoxydocosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7Z,10Z,13Z,19Z)-16,17-epoxydocosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7Z,10Z,16Z,19Z)-13,14-epoxydocosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-10,11-epoxydocosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-20-hydroxydocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid and sulfate functions of lithocholic acid sulfate; major species at pH 7.3.
A pentol that is 12,16-dimethylicosan-2-one in which the five hydroxy substituents are located at positions 3, 5, 10, 14 and 15.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxy-17beta-estradiol 3-sulfate, obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group.
A   thiazolidinemonocarboxylate anion resulting from proton loss from the carboxy group located on the beta-lactam ring of amoxicilloic acid.
An organic sodium salt that is the monosodium salt of amoxicilloic acid.
A thiazolidinemonocarboxylate formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of amoxicilloyl-butylamine.
A monocarboxylic acid anion comprising any thiazolidine carrying a single carboxylate substiuent.
An organic sodium salt that is the monosodium salt of amoxicilloyl-butylamine.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,11Z,13Z,15E,17S,19Z)-10,17-bis(hydroperoxy)docosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A hydroperoxydocosapentaenoate that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,11Z,13Z,15E,17S)-10,17-bis(hydroperoxy)docosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroperoxydocosapentaenoate that is the conjugate base of (7Z,11Z,13Z,15E,19Z)-10,17-bis(hydroperoxy)docosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Poly-L-lysine (n > 40) in which 50-70% of the epsilon-amino groups are substituted with amoxicilloyl groups.
A member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 2H-pyran-2-one which is substituted at positions 4 and 6 by hydroxy and acetonyl groups, respectively.
A tetronic acid derivative that is furan-2(5H)-one which is substituted at positions 3, 4, and 5 by butanoyl, hydroxy, and carboxymethyl groups, respectively (the S enantiomer).
The methyl ester of carlosic acid.
A butenolide that is the methyl ester of 4-(4-hydroxy-5-methylidene-2-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-yl)-4-oxobutanoic acid

An oligopeptide that is octa-L-lysine (Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys-Lys) in which each lysine residue is substituted on the epsilon-nitrogen by a benzylpenicilloyl group; used in skin-testing for penicillin allergy.
A dihydroxybenzaldehyde that is 2,4-dihydroxybenzaldehyde in which all three phenyl hydrogens have been replaced by methyl groups.
A dihydroxybenzaldehyde that is 2,4-dihydroxybenzaldehyde in which the hydrogens at positions 3, 5, and 6 have been replaced by methyl, methyl, and ethyl groups, respectively.
Any methoxyisoflavone which has a methoxy group at the 4-position of the phenyl substituent.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of aflatoxin B1 dialdehyde, obtained by deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'-5' triphosphate bridge to an initiating purine ribonucleotide
A 7-methyl guanosine (m7G) linked via an inverted 5'-5' triphosphate bridge to an initiating 2'-O-methyl-purine-ribonucleotide
An iminium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group of any N-retinylidene-N-retinylphosphatidylethanolamine.

A member of the class of benzoic acids that is benzoic acid which is substituted at positions 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6 by carbamoyl, hydroxy, E)-prop-1-en-1-yl, methyl, and methoxy groups, respectively. Obtained from solid-state fermentation of Aspergillus niger CFR-W-105, it inhibits soy bean lipoxygenase-1 (LOX-1) and rat lens aldose reductase (RLAR). It also shows free radical scavenging activity.
A nitroalkane in which the nitro group is attached to a terminal carbon. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.

A tricarboxylic acid that is hexa-2,4-dienedioic acid which is substituted at position 3 by a 2-carboxy-1-hydroxyethyl group (the 2Z,4E isomer; a mixture of isomers at the carbon bearing the alcoholic hydroxy group). It has been produced from trans-caffeic acid using Aspergillus niger, but the conversion rate was increased 3.5 times by using a coculture of Streptomyces coelicolor and Aspergillus niger.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of 12-oxo-6-trans-leukotriene B4, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of Delta(6)-trans-12-epi-leukotriene B4, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.

A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the beta-lactam-derived carboxy group of sodium amoxicilloate. The free valence at the acetyl group may form an amide linkage to the primary amino group of a protein carrier [e.g. human serum albumin (HSA)].
An S-substituted glutathione(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the the two carboxy groups and protonation of the glutamyl amino group of S-(2,4-dinitrophenyl)glutathione. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 17alpha-ethynylestradiol 3-sulfate arising from deprotonation of the sulfate OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-monoglyceride resulting from the condensation of the carboxy group of prostaglandin D2 with the 2-hydroxy group of glycerol.
A polyanionic polymer derived from oxidised coenzyme F420-(gamma-Glu)n. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
A very long-chain primary fatty alcohol that is heptacosane in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
